{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:46:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:46:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.05,0.82,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10138"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10138"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56315"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5332"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization\u0027s definition of health has remained largely unchanged since 1948. This definition emphasises that health encompasses more than just physical wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the World Health Organization\u0027s definition of health?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Freedom from pain and disability","Optimal physiological functioning of body systems","Absence of disease or infirmity","Complete physical, mental and social well-being","Ability to perform daily activities independently"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization defines health as a state of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete physical, mental and social well-being\u003C/strong\u003E, and not merely the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of disease or infirmity\u003C/strong\u003E. This definition revolutionised our understanding of health by moving beyond a purely biomedical model to include psychological and social dimensions.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFreedom from pain and disability\u003C/strong\u003E focuses solely on physical symptoms and does not acknowledge the broader aspects of wellbeing.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptimal physiological functioning of body systems\u003C/strong\u003E considers only the physical aspects of health whilst ignoring mental and social dimensions.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbility to perform daily activities independently\u003C/strong\u003E represents only one component of health and fails to capture the holistic nature of wellbeing.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThis comprehensive definition acknowledges that health is influenced by multiple factors including social determinants such as education, income, housing, and access to healthcare services. It forms the basis for understanding health inequities and developing holistic approaches to healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The World Health Organization defines health as a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being, not merely the absence of disease.","Social determinants of health include education, income, housing, and access to healthcare services.","Health inequities are systematic differences in health outcomes between different population groups that are avoidable and unfair."],"references":["Constitution of the World Health Organisation. WHO. Available from: https://www.who.int/about/governance/constitution","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:36:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:37:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10138"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"